## Natural 3 Carat Emerald Cut Diamond Ring Prices

Natural 3ct emerald cuts in certified market inventory run from $63,000 to $80,000+ for the stone alone at quality grades appropriate for this shape. The entry point — F-VS1 GIA — costs $63,574. The premium tier — D-FL GIA — reaches $77,542 for the stone.

[![Emerald cut diamond engagement ring yellow gold solitaire with melee band](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/501150/501150_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_Y_Box5_003_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Diamond</th><th>Cert</th><th>Colour / Clarity</th><th>Stone Price</th><th>+ Riviera Pavé WG $1,515</th><th>Total Ring</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/15813280?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3.09ct GIA Ideal Emerald</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>F / VS1</td><td><strong>$63,574</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$65,089</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27776595?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3.59ct GIA Ideal Emerald</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>G / VVS1</td><td><strong>$72,542</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$74,057</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27782883?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3.07ct GIA Ideal Emerald</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>D / FL</td><td><strong>$77,542</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$79,057</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/16900783?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3.54ct GIA Ideal Emerald</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>G / VVS2</td><td><strong>$78,922</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$80,437</strong></td></tr></tbody></table>

**Reading this table.** The [3.09ct GIA F-VS1 at $65,089 total](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/15813280?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the most efficient natural 3ct pick in this dataset. F colour in a step-cut's large open facets is the sweet spot — colourless in any metal, no colour warmth visible in the long mirror-like flashes. VS1 is the non-negotiable clarity floor for a 3ct emerald cut. At 9.5mm × 6.7mm face-up, every inclusion grade below VS1 is visible to the naked eye in the open table.

The [3.59ct G-VVS1 at $74,057 total](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27776595?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) offers more carat weight at a lower colour grade. G colour at 3ct in an emerald cut is a trade-off — in yellow or rose gold, G reads as completely colourless. In white gold or platinum, G at 3ct may show a very subtle warmth in the long step-cut mirrors to a trained eye. If your setting is white gold or platinum, stay at F or above for natural.

The [3.07ct D-FL at $79,057 total](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27782883?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is a collector stone. D colour, internally flawless, GIA-certified. This is auction-grade quality in a private sale setting. If you are buying for investment and provenance as much as beauty, this is the natural 3ct pick.

> "Natural 3ct emerald cuts are some of the rarest stones I audit. The emerald cut requires VS1+ clarity because the open table hides nothing. Finding a clean 3ct+ rough that yields a properly proportioned step-cut is genuinely difficult. That is why the prices start at $63,000.
>
> My consistent advice at natural 3ct: if your budget is under $70,000, the F-VS1 is the correct stone. Don't sacrifice clarity for colour or size — the hall-of-mirrors effect at 3ct depends on a clean stone. A VS2 natural emerald cut at 3ct can look foggy and dull. At 9.5mm × 6.7mm face-up, inclusions are visible from arm's length." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

