## Lab 3 Carat Emerald Cut Diamond Ring: The Full Value Case

The lab 3ct emerald cut market is where the natural vs lab comparison reaches its most extreme expression.

Natural 3ct F-VS1: $63,574 stone, $65,089 total ring.
Lab 3ct D-IF: $9,235 stone, $10,750 total ring.

Same physical size. Higher lab grades (D-IF vs F-VS1). $54,339 cheaper.

[![Emerald cut diamond engagement ring yellow gold pavé band packshot on white](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/501830/501830_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_Y_Box4_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Diamond</th><th>Cert</th><th>Colour / Clarity</th><th>Stone Price</th><th>+ Riviera Pavé WG $1,515</th><th>Total Ring</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3ct IGI D-IF Ideal Lab</a></td><td>IGI</td><td>D / IF</td><td><strong>$9,235</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$10,750</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25630282?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3ct IGI D-IF Ideal Lab</a></td><td>IGI</td><td>D / IF</td><td><strong>$9,619</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$11,134</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29354702?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3ct GCAL D-VVS1 Excellent Lab</a></td><td>GCAL</td><td>D / VVS1</td><td><strong>$10,695</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$12,210</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">4ct IGI D-VVS1 Lab</a></td><td>IGI</td><td>D / VVS1</td><td><strong>$7,737</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$9,252</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28857918?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">5ct IGI E-VVS1 Lab</a></td><td>IGI</td><td>E / VVS1</td><td><strong>$8,210</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$9,725</strong></td></tr></tbody></table>

**The counterintuitive data point.** The [lab 4ct D-VVS1 totals $9,252](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The lab 3ct D-IF totals $10,750. The 4ct is bigger and cheaper. This is not a typo. Lab diamond pricing is supply-driven, not size-driven. At the moment this data was captured, 4ct D-VVS1 lab supply was more abundant than 3ct D-IF lab supply — making the 4ct less expensive per stone. If you are buying lab and your goal is maximum size and quality for your money, the [4ct D-VVS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the stronger buy than the 3ct.

**Reading the lab table.** The [3ct IGI D-IF Ideal at $10,750 total](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the best stone in the 3ct lab market for a certified ring purchase. D colour in the emerald cut's large open table is completely colourless in any metal. IF (internally flawless) means the open table shows zero inclusions under any magnification. At 9.5mm × 6.7mm face-up, an IF stone at 3ct produces the hall-of-mirrors effect in its cleanest possible form — long, uninterrupted mirrored flashes with no visible characteristics to interrupt the reflection.

The GCAL 3ct D-VVS1 at $12,210 total is also a strong certified choice. GCAL (Gem Certification and Assurance Lab) is a reputable certification body. VVS1 at 3ct is eye-clean in any emerald cut. The $12,210 total ring is slightly higher than the IGI D-IF — worth considering if you prefer GCAL certification for any reason.

> "The lab 3ct emerald cut market is the one that consistently surprises buyers the most. They come in expecting to pay $30,000–$40,000 for a 3ct ring. The actual price is $10,750 for a D-IF certified stone. That gap never gets smaller — it consistently exceeds expectations.
>
> What I tell every lab 3ct buyer: check the 4ct stones before you commit. At the time of this audit, a [4ct D-VVS1 totals $9,252](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — less money, more stone. Lab pricing can make larger stones more accessible than smaller ones. Always look one size up before finalizing." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

